  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Geneva Study Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cverse2",
        "text": "And they set the priests in their divisions, and the Levites in their courses, for the service of God, which is at Jerusalem; as it is written in the book of Moses.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the priests in their divisions",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", &c.] The verse refers to the organization of the priests and Levites described in 1 Chronicles 23-26. According to this arrangement, the service of the Temple was distributed by periods, of a week each, among the courses and divisions of priests and Levites (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 11:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 23:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "On the “divisions” of the priests, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 1:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 1:8-9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "for the service of God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ‘Service’, the same word as that rendered ‘work’ in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 4:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But there ‘the work of the house of God’ refers to he building; here ‘the work or service of God’ refers to the worship. Compare the word ‘liturgy’ (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "λειτουργία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and the growth of its special application.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "as it is written in the book of Moses",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The reference seems to be to the Levitical arrangements generally upon which the Davidic and Solomonic organization was founded, as described in the books of Chronicles. Special mention of the ordering of the priests and Levites occurs in Numbers 3, 8.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "This verse concludes the Aramaic section (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 4:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 6:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 18.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "They",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "set the priests in their divisions, and the Levites in their courses.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The completion of the new temple was naturally followed by an arrangement of the ministers corresponding to that which had been originally made by David, and afterwards adopted by Solomon, for the service of the old temple (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 23:6-23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 24:1-19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This arrangement was based upon the ordinances of the law with respect to the respective offices of the two orders, as given in the Book of Numbers (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 3:6-10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 8:6-26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and, so far, was ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "according to the writing of the book of Moses.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " But the \"courses\" themselves were not established till David's time. CELEBRATION OF THE PASSOVER IN THE ENSUING MONTH, AND OBSERVANCE OF THE FEAST OF UNLEAVENED BREAD (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 6:19-22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Specially solemn passovers were celebrated on specially solemn occasions; and these received special record at the hands of the sacred writers. Of this kind are the passover celebrated By Hezekiah in the year  ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "date",
        "text": "B.C. 726",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", recorded in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and that celebrated by Josiah in  ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "date",
        "text": "B.C. 624",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", recorded in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Both of these followed upon a cleansing of the temple, and restoration of the temple worship after a period of suspension. Ezra seems to place the passover of  ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "date",
        "text": "B.C. 516",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in the same category. It marked the period of the full re-establishment of the regular ordinances of religion, more or less interrupted from the time of the destruction of the temple by Nebuchadnezzar. It terminated the abnormal and commenced the normal condition of things. Perhaps it is to mark this, that Ezra at this point disuses the Chaldee dialect, which he had introduced in ch. 4:8, and returns to the Hebrew, the established language of the Jewish religion. Ezra 6:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "At the same time, the priests and Levites were appointed, according to their classes and divisions, to the service of the temple, that they might henceforth fulfil their office, each class in its week (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 23:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 11:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). והקימוּ corresponds with the Hebrew ויּעמידוּ, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 3:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and elsewhere. As Bertheau justly remarks, \"The services of public worship, which after the completion of the temple were to be performed by the priests and Levites, according to ancient ordinance, are here spoken of.\" With these words the Chaldee section closes. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]